guage. [[Language loss]] occurs when the language has no more native speakers and becomes a [[dead language]].\n\n25 endangered Turkic languages exist in the world. The number of speakers are derived from statistics or estimates (2019) and were rounded:<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.unesco.org/languages-atlas/index.php?hl=en&page=atlasmap# | title=UNESCO Atlas of the World's Languages in danger}}</ref>  <ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/culture/themes/endangered-languages/atlas-of-languages-in-danger/ | title=Atlas of languages in danger &#124; United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=30|Number\n!width=200|Name\n!width=150|Status\n!width=100|Speakers\n!width=100|Main Country\n|-\n| align=center|1\n| [[Bashkir language]] || align=center|Vulnerable || align=center|1,500,000 || {{RUS}}\n|-\n| align=center|2\n| [[Chuvash language]] || align=center|Vulnerable || align=center|1,200,000 || {{RUS}}\n|-\n| align=center|3\n| [[Khorasani Turkic language]] || align=center|Vulnerable || align=center|1,000,000 || {{IRI}}\n|-\n| align=center|4\n| [[Crimean Tatar language]] || align=center|Severely endangered || align=center|600,000 || {{UKR}}\n|-\n| align=center|5\n| [[Kumyk language]] || align=center|Vulnerable || align=center|450,000 || {{RUS}}\n|-\n| align=center|6\n| [[Yakut language]] || align=center|Vulnerable || align=center|400,000 || {{RUS}}\n|-\n| align=center|7\n| [[Karachay-Balkar language]] || align=center|Vulnerable || align=center|400,000 || {{RUS}}\n|-\n| align=center|8\n| [[Tuvan language]] || align=center|Vulnerable || align=center|300,000 || {{RUS}}\n|-\n| align=center|9\n| [[Urum language]] || align=center|Definitely endangered || align=center|200,000 || {{UKR}}\n|-\n| align=center|10\n| [[Gagauz language]] || align=center|Critically endangered || align=center|150,000 || {{MDA}}\n|-\n| align=center|11\n| [[Siberian Tatar language]] || align=center|Definitely endang