guage]] || align=center|Severely endangered || align=center|100 || {{CHN}}\n|-\n| align=center|25\n| [[Chulym language]] || align=center|Critically endangered || align=center|50 || {{RUS}}\n|}\n\n=== Russia ===\n{{main|List of endangered languages in Russia|Languages of Russia}}\n\n14 endangered Turkic languages exist in Russia:<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.unesco.org/languages-atlas/index.php?hl=en&page=atlasmap# | title=UNESCO Atlas of the World's Languages in danger}}</ref>  <ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/culture/themes/endangered-languages/atlas-of-languages-in-danger/ | title=Atlas of languages in danger &#124; United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=30|Number\n!width=200|Name\n!width=150|Status\n!width=100|Speakers\n|-\n| align=center|1\n| [[Bashkir language]] || align=center|Vulnerable || align=center|1,500,000\n|-\n| align=center|2\n| [[Chuvash language]] || align=center|Vulnerable || align=center|1,200,000\n|-\n| align=center|3\n| [[Crimean Tatar language]] || align=center|Severely endangered || align=center|600,000\n|-\n| align=center|4\n| [[Kumyk language]] || align=center|Vulnerable || align=center|450,000\n|-\n| align=center|5\n| [[Yakut language]] || align=center|Vulnerable || align=center|400,000\n|-\n| align=center|6\n| [[Karachay-Balkar language]] || align=center|Vulnerable || align=center|400,000\n|-\n| align=center|7\n| [[Tuvan language]] || align=center|Vulnerable || align=center|300,000\n|-\n| align=center|8\n| [[Siberian Tatar language]] || align=center|Definitely endangered || align=center|100,000\n|-\n| align=center|9\n| [[Nogai language]] || align=center|Definitely endangered || align=center|100,000\n|-\n| align=center|10\n| [[Altai language]] || align=center|Severely endangered || align=center|60,000\n|-\n| align=center|11\n| [[Khakas language]] || align=center|Definitely endangered || align=center|50,000\n|-\n| align=center|12\n| [[Shor l